Note:
==============================================================================
CRYPTO_ALGORITHM - Algorithm Tag Types (Tier 1 crypto identity primitive)
==============================================================================

Defines stable integer algorithm identifiers for every cryptographic primitive
in the Runa standard crypto suite. Algorithm-tagged values carry their algorithm
alongside their key/signature/hash bytes so the type system can prevent
cross-algorithm confusion attacks (e.g., feeding an Ed25519 public key into an
ECDSA verify path, which has caused real production CVEs).

Per HC#11 (TASC), no cryptographic primitive in Runa is selected by string
comparison or by inspection of byte length alone; every surface dispatches on
the algorithm tag carried with the material.

The tag ranges are partitioned so subset predicates (signature vs KEM vs hash
vs AEAD vs KDF) are O(1) range tests:
  -    0       : ALG_UNKNOWN
  -    1.. 99  : reserved
  -  100..199  : signature schemes (classical and post-quantum)
  -  200..299  : KEM and key-agreement schemes
  -  300..399  : hash algorithms
  -  400..499  : AEAD algorithms
  -  500..599  : KDF algorithms
  -  600..    : reserved for future use

The integer tags are stable across releases. Their numeric values MUST NOT be
reused even if an algorithm is deprecated; deprecated algorithms keep their
slot to ensure persisted artifacts (signed messages, stored keys, sealed
ciphertexts) remain unambiguously dispatchable.

References:
- HC#11 TASC: crypto-suite selection mandate.
- RFC 8032: Ed25519 / Ed448 signatures.
- FIPS 186-5: ECDSA over NIST curves.
- RFC 8017: RSASSA-PSS and RSASSA-PKCS1-v1_5.
- FIPS 203: ML-KEM (Module-Lattice KEM).
- FIPS 204: ML-DSA (Module-Lattice DSA).
- FIPS 205: SLH-DSA (Stateless Hash-based DSA).
- FALCON round-3 spec (NIST PQC).
- FIPS 180-4 / FIPS 202: SHA-2 / SHA-3 / SHAKE.
- BLAKE3 spec (O'Connor, Aumasson, Neves, Wilcox-O'Hearn 2020).
- RFC 7693: BLAKE2.
- NIST SP 800-38D: AES-GCM.
- RFC 8452: AES-GCM-SIV.
- RFC 8439: ChaCha20-Poly1305.
- libsodium docs: XChaCha20-Poly1305.
- RFC 5869: HKDF.
- RFC 9106: Argon2id.
- RFC 7914: scrypt.
- RFC 8018: PBKDF2.
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1: Algorithm identifier constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: ----- Sentinel value -----
Let ALG_UNKNOWN be 0

Note: ----- Classical signature schemes (100-149) -----
Let ALG_ED25519 be 100
Let ALG_ED448 be 101
Let ALG_ECDSA_P256 be 102
Let ALG_ECDSA_P384 be 103
Let ALG_ECDSA_P521 be 104

Note:
==============================================================================
RSA signature schemes (110-149)

RSA signature tags encode BOTH the hash algorithm AND the modulus size. This
is required because RFC 4055 / RFC 8017 bind the signature's security to a
specific (padding, hash, modulus) triple, and dispatching on modulus alone
(the historical mistake corrected in this revision) drops the hash binding
and causes SHA-384/SHA-512 RSA signatures to be verified against the wrong
digest. The numeric slots are stable; future deprecations of any tag MUST
retain the slot per the section-1 header.

Slot layout:
  PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA family (110..118): SHA-256 (110-112), SHA-384 (113-115),
                                     SHA-512 (116-118). Each hash block
                                     orders moduli 2048, 3072, 4096.
  RSASSA-PSS family (120..128):      Same ordering. For PSS the
                                     hashAlgorithm and mgf1 hash are bound
                                     equal per RFC 8017.

The rsa_alg_modulus_bytes helper below reads the slot offset to recover the
modulus size; rsa_alg_to_rsa_hash_id maps to the RSA module's internal hash
identifier; rsa_alg_is_pss distinguishes the two families.
:End Note
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA256_2048 be 110
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA256_3072 be 111
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA256_4096 be 112
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA384_2048 be 113
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA384_3072 be 114
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA384_4096 be 115
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA512_2048 be 116
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA512_3072 be 117
Let ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA512_4096 be 118
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA256_2048 be 120
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA256_3072 be 121
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA256_4096 be 122
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA384_2048 be 123
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA384_3072 be 124
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA384_4096 be 125
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA512_2048 be 126
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA512_3072 be 127
Let ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA512_4096 be 128

Note: ----- Post-quantum signature schemes (150-199) -----
Let ALG_ML_DSA_44 be 150
Let ALG_ML_DSA_65 be 151
Let ALG_ML_DSA_87 be 152
Let ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S be 160
Let ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F be 161
Let ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S be 162
Let ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F be 163
Let ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S be 164
Let ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F be 165
Let ALG_FALCON_512 be 170
Let ALG_FALCON_1024 be 171

Note: ----- Key agreement / KEM (200-299) -----
Let ALG_X25519 be 200
Let ALG_X448 be 201
Let ALG_ML_KEM_512 be 220
Let ALG_ML_KEM_768 be 221
Let ALG_ML_KEM_1024 be 222

Note: ----- Hash algorithms (300-399) -----
Let ALG_SHA2_256 be 300
Let ALG_SHA2_384 be 301
Let ALG_SHA2_512 be 302
Let ALG_SHA3_256 be 310
Let ALG_SHA3_384 be 311
Let ALG_SHA3_512 be 312
Let ALG_BLAKE3 be 320
Let ALG_BLAKE2B_256 be 330
Let ALG_BLAKE2B_512 be 331
Let ALG_BLAKE2S be 332
Let ALG_KECCAK_256 be 340

Note: ----- AEAD algorithms (400-499) -----
Let ALG_AES_128_GCM be 400
Let ALG_AES_256_GCM be 401
Let ALG_AES_128_GCM_SIV be 410
Let ALG_AES_256_GCM_SIV be 411
Let ALG_CHACHA20_POLY1305 be 420
Let ALG_XCHACHA20_POLY1305 be 421

Note: ----- KDF algorithms (500-599) -----
Let ALG_HKDF_SHA256 be 500
Let ALG_HKDF_SHA384 be 501
Let ALG_HKDF_SHA512 be 502
Let ALG_HKDF_BLAKE3 be 510
Let ALG_ARGON2ID be 520
Let ALG_SCRYPT be 521
Let ALG_PBKDF2_HMAC_SHA256 be 530
Let ALG_PBKDF2_HMAC_SHA512 be 531

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2: Category predicates (O(1) range tests)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is a signature algorithm identifier, 0 otherwise. Signature
algorithms occupy the contiguous range 100..199 (classical 100..149,
post-quantum 150..199). The range test is constant-time with respect to the
input value, but algorithm identity itself is not a secret.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if (alg is in 100..199), 0 otherwise. Implemented as two integer
comparisons; no allocation, no branching on secret data.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). Two integer compares plus one boolean and.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret metadata. No timing side-channel concern.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_signature" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is less than 100:
        Return 0
    End If
    If alg is greater than 199:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is a KEM or key-agreement algorithm identifier. KEM and
key-agreement share the same numeric range (200..299) because both produce a
shared secret from a (public, ephemeral) pair, and the dispatch tables that
handle them share the same interface shape (encapsulate / decapsulate or
derive). Callers that care about the distinction inspect the specific tag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if (alg is in 200..299), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_kem_or_kex" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is less than 200:
        Return 0
    End If
    If alg is greater than 299:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is a hash algorithm identifier. Hash algorithms occupy the
range 300..399.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if (alg is in 300..399), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_hash" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is less than 300:
        Return 0
    End If
    If alg is greater than 399:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is an AEAD algorithm identifier. AEAD algorithms occupy the
range 400..499.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if (alg is in 400..499), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_aead" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is less than 400:
        Return 0
    End If
    If alg is greater than 499:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is a KDF algorithm identifier. KDF algorithms occupy the
range 500..599.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if (alg is in 500..599), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_kdf" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is less than 500:
        Return 0
    End If
    If alg is greater than 599:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is recognized by this Runa build. Useful for input validation
at boundaries between trusted code and external input (parsed protocol headers,
on-disk artifacts, RPC parameters). Unknown algorithm tags must NEVER select a
default; callers must reject the input.

Per HC#11, algorithm dispatch never defaults silently. This predicate is the
single point that decides whether a tag is dispatchable at all.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if any category predicate matches, 0 otherwise. The empty zero slot
and reserved bands are explicitly NOT recognized.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). At most five compares.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret. This is an authorization-style predicate: false
return MUST result in caller-side rejection, never in a default selection.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_recognized" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If algorithm_is_signature(alg) is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If algorithm_is_kem_or_kex(alg) is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If algorithm_is_hash(alg) is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If algorithm_is_aead(alg) is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If algorithm_is_kdf(alg) is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3: Post-quantum / classical classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is a post-quantum cryptographic algorithm, 0 otherwise.
Post-quantum algorithms are those resistant to Shor's algorithm on a
cryptographically-relevant quantum computer (CRQC). Used by the crypto-
agility layer to decide migration urgency and by validators that enforce a
PQ-only or hybrid-PQ policy on signed artifacts.

Per NIST PQC standardization round 3 winners (selected 2022, finalized 2024
in FIPS 203, 204, 205) and the FALCON specification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if alg is one of the ML-KEM, ML-DSA, SLH-DSA, or FALCON identifiers.
Returns 0 for classical and unknown identifiers. The decision is by explicit
enumeration rather than by range because the post-quantum identifiers are
scattered across the signature (150..199) and KEM (220..229) ranges to
preserve the category invariants of section 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). Up to 11 integer compares (12 PQ identifiers minus structural overlap).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Algorithm tag is non-secret. False return is informational, not security-
relevant by itself.

References:
- FIPS 203 (ML-KEM, formerly CRYSTALS-Kyber).
- FIPS 204 (ML-DSA, formerly CRYSTALS-Dilithium).
- FIPS 205 (SLH-DSA, formerly SPHINCS+).
- FALCON: Fast-Fourier Lattice-based Compact Signatures over NTRU, Round-3.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_post_quantum" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_44:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_65:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_87:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_FALCON_512:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_FALCON_1024:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_512:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_768:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_1024:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns 1 if alg is a classical (non-post-quantum) signature, KEM, or
key-agreement algorithm. Hash, AEAD, and KDF algorithms are not classified
classical-or-PQ; they return 0 from both predicates.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 for the explicit classical-asymmetric identifiers, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Non-secret metadata.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_is_classical" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is equal to ALG_ED25519:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ED448:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA256_2048:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA256_3072:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA256_4096:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA384_2048:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA384_3072:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA384_4096:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA512_2048:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA512_3072:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PKCS1V15_SHA512_4096:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA256_2048:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA256_3072:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA256_4096:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA384_2048:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA384_3072:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA384_4096:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA512_2048:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA512_3072:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_RSA_PSS_SHA512_4096:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_X25519:
        Return 1
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_X448:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4: Algorithm metadata (key sizes, signature sizes, security bits)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the canonical public-key byte length for alg, or 0 if alg has no
fixed-length public key (e.g., RSA, whose modulus length is variable) or if
alg is not an asymmetric scheme. Used by public_key.runa to validate at
construction time that the provided key bytes match the declared algorithm.

Per RFC 8032 (Ed25519/Ed448), FIPS 186-5 (ECDSA), and the NIST PQC
specifications.

Fixed sizes (bytes):
  Ed25519:       32     (RFC 8032 5.1.5)
  Ed448:         57     (RFC 8032 5.2.5)
  ECDSA-P256:    65     (uncompressed SEC1: 0x04 || X || Y, 1+32+32)
  ECDSA-P384:    97     (1+48+48)
  ECDSA-P521:    133    (1+66+66)
  X25519:        32     (RFC 7748)
  X448:          56     (RFC 7748)
  ML-KEM-512:    800    (FIPS 203 Table 3)
  ML-KEM-768:    1184
  ML-KEM-1024:   1568
  ML-DSA-44:     1312   (FIPS 204 Table 1)
  ML-DSA-65:     1952
  ML-DSA-87:     2592
  SLH-DSA-128S:  32     (FIPS 205 Table 2)
  SLH-DSA-128F:  32
  SLH-DSA-192S:  48
  SLH-DSA-192F:  48
  SLH-DSA-256S:  64
  SLH-DSA-256F:  64
  FALCON-512:    897    (FALCON round-3 spec)
  FALCON-1024:   1793
RSA algorithms return 0 because the public-key length is implied by the
modulus length, which is a per-key property, not an algorithm property.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lookup by integer comparison against each tag. Returns 0 for variable-length
algorithms and unknown tags.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) constant-time lookup.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Non-secret metadata. Length validation at construction time prevents
algorithm-mismatch attacks that rely on the verifier accepting a malformed
key as a different algorithm's key.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_key_byte_length" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is equal to ALG_ED25519:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ED448:
        Return 57
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Return 65
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Return 97
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Return 133
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_X25519:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_X448:
        Return 56
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_512:
        Return 800
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_768:
        Return 1184
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_1024:
        Return 1568
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_44:
        Return 1312
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_65:
        Return 1952
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_87:
        Return 2592
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S:
        Return 48
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F:
        Return 48
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S:
        Return 64
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F:
        Return 64
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_FALCON_512:
        Return 897
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_FALCON_1024:
        Return 1793
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the canonical private-key byte length for alg. Asymmetric algorithms
distinguish public and private key sizes; this is the SECRET-KEY size per
spec. RSA returns 0 (variable). Hash, AEAD, KDF, key-agreement-shared-secret
return 0 (no concept of private key).

Sizes (bytes):
  Ed25519:       32     (seed; expanded key is 64 but seed defines identity)
  Ed448:         57
  ECDSA-P256:    32     (32-byte scalar)
  ECDSA-P384:    48
  ECDSA-P521:    66
  X25519:        32
  X448:          56
  ML-KEM-512:    1632   (FIPS 203 Table 3 decapsulation key size)
  ML-KEM-768:    2400
  ML-KEM-1024:   3168
  ML-DSA-44:     2560   (FIPS 204 Table 1)
  ML-DSA-65:     4032
  ML-DSA-87:     4896
  SLH-DSA-128S:  64     (FIPS 205 Table 2)
  SLH-DSA-128F:  64
  SLH-DSA-192S:  96
  SLH-DSA-192F:  96
  SLH-DSA-256S:  128
  SLH-DSA-256F:  128
  FALCON-512:    1281   (encoded private key length, FALCON round-3 spec)
  FALCON-1024:   2305
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lookup by integer comparison.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Length metadata is non-secret, but the SECRET-KEY VALUES themselves are
strictly secret. This proc returns only the length, never key material.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "algorithm_private_key_byte_length" takes alg as Integer returns Integer:
    If alg is equal to ALG_ED25519:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ED448:
        Return 57
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Return 48
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Return 66
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_X25519:
        Return 32
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_X448:
        Return 56
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_512:
        Return 1632
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_768:
        Return 2400
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_KEM_1024:
        Return 3168
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_44:
        Return 2560
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_65:
        Return 4032
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_ML_DSA_87:
        Return 4896
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S:
        Return 64
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F:
        Return 64
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S:
        Return 96
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F:
        Return 96
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S:
        Return 128
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F:
        Return 128
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_FALCON_512:
        Return 1281
    End If
    If alg is equal to ALG_FALCON_1024:
        Return 2305
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the canonical signature byte length for alg, or 0 for non-signature
algorithms or signature schemes with variable-length output. FALCON has
variable-length signatures (the value here is the MAXIMUM size); callers
must use the size encoded in the FALCON signature header.

Sizes (bytes):
  Ed25519:                    64     (RFC 8032 5.1.6: R||S)
  Ed448:                      114    (RFC 8032 5.2.6)
  ECDSA-P256 raw r||s:        64     (32-byte r + 32-byte s)
  ECDSA-P384 raw r||s:        96
  ECDSA-P521 raw r||s:        132
  RSA-PSS-2048:               256
  RSA-PSS-3072:               384
  RSA-PSS-4096:               512
  RSA-PKCS1v15-2048:          256
  RSA-PKCS1v15-3072:          384
  RSA-PKCS1v15-4096:          512
  ML-DSA-44:                  2420   (FIPS 204 Table 1)
  ML-DSA-65:                  3309
  ML-DSA-87:                  4627
  SLH-DSA-128S:               7856   (FIPS 205 Table 2)
  SLH-DSA-128F:               17088
  SLH-DSA-192S:               16224
  SLH-DSA-192F:               35664
  SLH-DSA-256S:               29792
  SLH-DSA-256F:               49856
  FALCON-512 max:             752    (FALCON spec)
  FALCON-1024 max:            1462
Note: ECDSA DER encoding is variable-length; this proc returns the raw
r||s length. DER framing adds 6..8 bytes depending on the high bit of r/s.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lookup by integer comparison.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Non-secret metadata. Length validation at signature construction prevents a
class of forgery attacks that rely on the verifier mistaking a truncated or
extended signature for a valid one.
@End Security_Scope
